# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1868-danish-west-indies-status-referendum] A referendum on transferring ownership to the United States was held on 9 January 1868 on the islands of Sankt Jan and Sankt Thomas, two of three main islands in the Danish West Indies.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1868-danish-west-indies-status-referendum] In the referendum, held by universal male suffrage, voters could approve or reject the outcome of negotiations for the sale of the two islands to the United States for US$7.5 million.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1868-danish-west-indies-status-referendum] The third island, Sankt Croix, was to be sold separately to the US at a later date.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1868-danish-west-indies-status-referendum] The sale was approved by 98.26% of voters.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1868-danish-west-indies-status-referendum] Although it was a binding referendum, the US Senate finally reneged on the agreement in 1870.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1868-danish-west-indies-status-referendum] The Islands were later transferred to the United States after a second referendum in 1916 and the subsequent Treaty of the Danish West Indies.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] A referendum on the sale of the Danish West Indian Islands to the United States of America was held in Denmark on 14 December 1916.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] The non-binding referendum saw 283,670 vote in favor of the sale of the Danish West Indian Islands and 158,157 against.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] The residents of the islands were not allowed to vote on the matter, but in an unofficial vote on Saint Croix arranged by David Hamilton Jackson, 4,027 voted in favor of the sale and only seven voted against.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] As a result of the referendum the islands were formally relinquished to the United States by the Treaty of the Danish West Indies on 31 March 1917 as the United States Virgin Islands for a sum of US$25,000,000 in gold.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] Two of the islands had been in Danish possession since the 17th century and Saint Croix since 1733.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] The highly profitable period of the colony had been from around 1750 to 1850 based on transit trade and the production of rum and sugar using African slaves as labor.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] At the negotiations for the Treaty of Vienna after the defeat in the Second Schleswig War in 1864, Denmark had tried to use the islands as a trade-in for South Jutland, but the Prussian Government was not interested.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] At the eve of the American Civil War, the United States became interested in the islands as the possible location of a Caribbean naval base.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] A referendum on transferring ownership from Denmark to the United States was held on 9 January 1868 on the islands of Sankt Jan and Sankt Thomas, two of three main islands in the colony.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] Of the votes cast, 98% were in favor of the transfer.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] On 24 October 1867 the Danish parliament, the Rigsdag, ratified a treaty on the sale of the two islands for a sum of US$7,500,000.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] However, the United States Senate did not ratify the treaty due to concerns over a number of natural disasters that had struck the islands and a political feud with and the possible impeachment of President Andrew Johnson.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] Negotiations resumed in 1899 following the unofficial diplomacy of Walter Christmas.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] On 24 January 1902 Washington signed a convention on the transfer of the islands for a sum of US$5,000,000.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] One chamber of the Danish parliament—the Folketing—passed the proposal, but in the other chamber—the Landsting—it failed with 32 votes against 32.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] In particular the conservative party Højre opposed it on the grounds that the treaty did not ensure the local population a vote on the matter, and that it did not grant them US citizenship or freedom from customs duty on the export of sugar to the United States.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] According to historian Povl Engelstoft, there was no doubt that Council President Johan Henrik Deuntzer was privately against the sale even though his party, the Venstre Reform Party, supported it.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] When the Landsting failed to pass the proposal, Deuntzer made a statement that neither did he see a reason for the cabinet to step down, nor would he dissolve the Landsting or assume responsibility for any further work related to the sale.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] Famous labor leader David Hamilton Jackson, made a visit to Copenhagen in May 1915.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] He successfully raised awareness of the growing social desperation on the islands and the need to enter the customs territory of the United States in order for the islands to be able to cope with their economic crisis.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] After his visit a majority of the Folketing was convinced that the Danish supremacy of the islands had to end.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] This would be unacceptable to the Americans as stated in the Monroe Doctrine.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] The Danish government was convinced that the islands had to be sold for the sake of both the residents and Danish security, and that a transfer would have to be realized before the United States entered the war, so that the transfer would not become a violation of the Danish neutrality.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] On 29 October 1915 United States Secretary of State Robert Lansing managed to reopen the negotiations.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] The negotiations, which lasted until August 1916, were kept absolutely secret in order to maintain the Danish neutrality.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] Although rumors of the future sale did leak to the press, they were denied categorically by both Scavenius and Minister of Finance Edvard Brandes.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] During 1916, the two sides agreed to a sale price of $25,000,000.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] The government informed the parliament of the negotiations and their result in August 1916, and the message aroused bitter feelings in particular among the conservatives and to some degree within Venstre.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] The outrage was partially based on the government's readiness to hand off a part of the kingdom for money and partially on the secrecy regarding all the preparations and that the denials by the two ministers had been completely contrary to facts.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] Those who opposed the sale now demanded that the treaty should be reviewed by a new parliament, with the intent to trigger a new election and hoping that the government would thereby lose its majority in the Folketing.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] In response, the government proposed a referendum on the issue as had recently become possible with the Constitution of 1915.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] The Landsting rejected this proposal, triggering a government crisis.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] The referendum would include voters in the Faroe Islands, but neither Iceland nor Greenland, nor would it include the West Indian Islands, and it would be non-binding in the sense that in the case of a majority in favor of the sale the parliament would still have the right to reject it.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] The commission published its report on 2 December with the recommendation to approve the sale.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] The referendum was held on 14 December 1916.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] As the Election Act of 1915, which significantly increased the number of eligible voters, was used for the referendum even though it did not otherwise take effect until 1918, the exact number of eligible voters is unknown, but has been estimated at 1,200,000.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] In an unofficial vote on Saint Croix arranged by Hamilton Jackson 4,027 voted in favor of the sale and only seven voted against.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] On 20 December the Danish parliament ratified the treaty, and on 9 March 1917 Christian X of Denmark officially said goodbye to the islands in an open letter.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] On 1 April the formal transfer of the islands took place, only five days before the United States declared war on Germany.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indian-islands-sale-referendum] In an attempt to create national reconciliation, most of the 25 million dollars was spent in Southern Jutland after the Schleswig Plebiscites and the return of the region to Danish rule in 1920.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum] An unofficial referendum on the sale of the islands to the United States was held in the Danish West Indies on 17 August 1916.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum] The proposal was approved by 99.83% of voters, with only seven people voting against.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum] It followed the Treaty of the Danish West Indies, which was signed on 4 August, and also approved by a referendum in Denmark in December 1916.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum] The islands were transferred to the United States in 1917.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum] No vote was held on Water Island, which had been sold by Denmark to the East Asiatic Company, a private shipping company, in 1905, and was no longer part of the colony.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] Pearson was born in Litchfield, Illinois.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] He attended Baker University in Baldwin City, Kansas, for his Master of Arts degree.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] In 1907 he was listed as one of the co-creators of *Lyceumite & Talent* magazine along with Louis J.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] In 1909, he obtained his doctorate at Northwestern University and did some teaching there, before moving to Swarthmore, Pennsylvania and becoming a professor of Public Speaking at Swarthmore College.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] He wrote several books on public speaking and was an editor of the quarterly magazine "The speaker".
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] He was also a major advocate of the Chautauqua movement in the US and founded the Swarthmore Chautauqua Association.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] Besides this he served as a speaker for the American Red Cross.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] During World War I, he was responsible for the YMCA education programs in United States Army cantonments.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] In 1896, he was married to Edna Rachel Wolfe Pearson (1874-1942), with whom he had four children, the oldest son being Drew Pearson, the well-known newspaper columnist and radio host.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] In 1931, Pearson was appointed by President Herbert Hoover to be the first civilian Governor of the United States Virgin Islands.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] His new government, inaugurated March 18, 1931, was given $763,000 ($8.5 million in inflation-adjusted 2005 dollars) to try and shore up the islands' finances which were badly hurt by Prohibition.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] (The primary export had been rum.) They were also given the task of replacing all military-government officials with new civilian ones, a task which they were required to complete within the first six months.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] President Hoover visited the Virgin Islands (and Puerto Rico) as a show of support for the new civilian administration.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] Less than a year after taking office, friction developed between the Governor and Herbert D.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] Brown, the chief of the Bureau of Efficiency.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] Brown had previously endorsed Pearson for the position, but by June 1931, he had requested to Hoover and the Department of the Interior that Pearson be replaced.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] This dispute was in large part financial.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] Under the military government, Brown had operated a quasi-civilian government in St.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] Croix since 1928, using money allocated to that purpose by Congress (for an "efficiency investigation").
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] Under the civilian government, this budget reverted to the new Governor.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] While Pearson largely implemented Brown's existing programs, he was no longer given direct authority.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] Pearson was also criticized for cronyism, including creating positions in his government (such as "Director of Adult Entertainment") which were given to friends from Pennsylvania.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] (Pearson rebutted that the positions were to help native morale.) On August 4, the Department of the Interior announced that Pearson would not be ousted from his position.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] Financial problems also plagued Pearson during his time as governor as the US government was providing $200,000 annually for aid.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] In November 1932, he proposed to Congress that the islands be allowed to export rum again, but only to foreigners so as not to violate Prohibition.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] However, this became moot when the 21st Amendment was ratified the following year.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] Pearson continued to be unpopular with the locals, especially after passing a law which taxed all imported products from the United States at 5%.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] On October 19, 1933, the populace of the Virgin Islands voted in a popular referendum whether or not to ask President Franklin D.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] Ninety-eight percent of those voting favored the removal of Pearson from office.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] In February 1934, Pearson declared personal bankruptcy, in large part due to debts incurred while working with his Chautauqua organization in Pennsylvania.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] In November 1934, a scandal erupted as Pearson's executive assistant, Paul C.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] Yates was fired by Secretary of the Interior Harold L.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] Ickes for "disloyalty" and "insubordination" and ordered him to return to Washington, D.C., for an investigation.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] Instead, Yates immediately resigned his position and traveled to Washington to meet with committees from both houses of Congress.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] He alleged to Congress that Ickes had been "outrageously deceived" by Pearson and that Pearson had been covering up scandals and mismanagement.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] Congress dispatched Ernest Gruening, the chief of the Bureau of Insular Affairs, Division of Territories and Island Possessions to the islands to investigate.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] Gruening found no mismanagement in his investigation.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] (Critics have pointed out that Gruening worked for Ickes and that he may not have been an unbiased investigator.) Despite this, on February 28, 1935, Congress voted to start their own independent investigation, to be led by Millard Tydings, a Senator.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] The Senate hearings continued, but President Roosevelt appointed Lawrence William Cramer as the new Governor.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] In 1935, Pearson returned to the mainland to work for the new United States Housing Authority.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1933-united-states-virgin-islands-governor-referendum] On February 28, 1938, he suffered a stroke while on a business trip to California to urge passage of a law to permit public housing in that State.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1940-united-states-virgin-islands-general-election] Elections were held on the islands of St.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1940-united-states-virgin-islands-general-election] John in the United States Virgin Islands on November 5, 1940, to elect 7 members of the Municipal Council.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1940-united-states-virgin-islands-general-election] The Progressive Guide won in a landslide, electing 6 of the 7 members.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1940-united-states-virgin-islands-general-election] The People's Civic League only won one seat, St.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1940-united-states-virgin-islands-general-election] John, as the Progressive Guide did not contest it.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1940-united-states-virgin-islands-general-election] Croix to elect 9 members to their own Municipal Council.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1948-united-states-virgin-islands-referendum] A **referendum on councils and treasury** was held in the United States Virgin Islands on 2 November 1948.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1948-united-states-virgin-islands-referendum] Hastie had requested the local parliament to draw up six referendum questions.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1948-united-states-virgin-islands-referendum] While this referendum was held alongside elections, turnout was only 60% that of the general election.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1953-united-states-virgin-islands-referendum] A **referendum on councils and treasury** was held in the United States Virgin Islands on 30 April 1953.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1953-united-states-virgin-islands-referendum] It was largely a repetition of the questions from the 1948 referendum.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1953-united-states-virgin-islands-referendum] The passage of all four questions in this referendum resulted in the 1954 Organic Act which governs relations with the United States of America to this day.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1962-united-states-virgin-islands-general-election] The **1962 United States Virgin Islands general election** was held on November 6, 1962, to elect members of the 5th Virgin Islands Legislature.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1962-united-states-virgin-islands-general-election] As this was before the 1966 Amending Act, no gubernatorial election took place.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1962-united-states-virgin-islands-general-election] The Unity Party, a party with no national affiliate, won a majority in the chamber.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1962-united-states-virgin-islands-general-election] Shortly after the beginning of the session, the Unity party changed their name to the Unity-Democratic party.
[src:1916-danish-west-indies-status-referendum/1962-united-states-virgin-islands-general-election] Ottley was elected president in the legislative session.
